  {
    "index": 3,
    "hash": "VKBSUEZDOXVRK5sZohuc8BkoIBk=",
    "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:37.000Z",
    "action": {
      "type": "SET_CONTENT",
      "input": {
        "content": "# never use toThrow when testing reducer errors\n\nThe most common testing mistake with Powerhouse reducers:\n\n```typescript\n// \u274c WRONG \u2014 this will always pass (no error is thrown to the caller)\nexpect(() => reducer(document, setName({ name: \"invalid\" }))).toThrow();\n\n// \u2705 CORRECT \u2014 check the operation's error property\nconst updated = reducer(document, setName({ name: \"invalid\" }));\nexpect(updated.operations.global[0].error).toBe(\"Name is not allowed\");\nexpect(updated.state.global.name).toBe(initialState); // state unchanged\n```\n\nSince [[operation errors are recorded on operations not thrown to callers]], the error is captured silently on the operation object. The reducer call itself never throws \u2014 it always returns a document. The error lives in `operations.global[N].error`.\n\nSince [[operation error index must match the number of prior dispatches]], make sure you check the right index.\n\n---\n\nTopics:\n- [[reducer patterns]]",
        "updatedAt": "2026-05-13T13:00:37.000Z"
      },
      "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:37.000Z"
    }
  },
